{"title_page": "Jennifer Bolande", "text_new": "{{short description|American artist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Jennifer Bolande\n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1957<!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place = [[Cleveland, Ohio]]\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nationality = American\n| spouse = \n| field = Visual Art\n| training = \n| alma_mater = [[NSCAD University]]\n| movement = Interdisciplinary\n| works = The Composition of Decomposition (2020), Visible Distance/Second Sight (2017), Tower of Movie Marquees, (2010) Milk Crown (1989)\n| patrons = \n| awards = [[Guggenheim Fellowship]], Andy Warhol Foundation Fellowship, NYFA, Tesuque Foundation\n| memorials = \n| elected = \n| website = https://jbolande.com/\n| bgcolour = \n| module = \n| residence = Los Angeles, United States\n| known_for = \n}}\n'''Jennifer Bolande''' is an American artist whose work employs various media\u2014primarily photography, sculpture, film and site-specific installations to explore the affinities between particular sets of objects and images and the mercurial meanings they manufacture.\n\nBolande emerged as an artist in the late 1970s, working initially in dance, choreography and drawing. In the early 1980s, she advanced the ideas and strategies proposed by the Pictures Generation Movement and began working with found images, re-photography, appropriation, film and installation, taking her place among those artists who have helped to redefine photography. She takes an intuitive approach to creating conceptual works in the construction of a coherent visual language.\u00a0 A retrospective exhibition of her work was organized in 2010 by the University of Wisconsin in Milwaukee, and traveled to the ICA in Philadelphia<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.jsonline.com/blogs/entertainment/94790029.html|title=A Conversation: Jennifer Bolande and David Robbins|website=archive.jsonline.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>, and the Luckman Gallery at California State University in Los Angeles. A monograph on her work was published by JRP|Ringier<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.artbook.com/9783037642603.html|title=Jennifer Bolande Landmarks ARTBOOK {{!}} D.A.P. 2011 Catalog JRP{{!}}Ringier Books Exhibition Catalogues 9783037642603}}</ref> in conjunction with the show.  Her award winning site-specific project \u201cVisible Distance/Second Sight\u201d was featured in the inaugural Desert Exhibition of Art, in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desertx.org/jennifer-bolande|title=Jennifer Bolande|website=Desert X|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>.  Her recent exhibition at Pio Pico Gallery, Los Angeles, titled \"The Composition of Decomposition,\" included a new body of works taking the newspaper as a point of departure for photographs, film and sculptural works <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jbolande.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/artforum_piopico_sml.pdf|title=\"Andrew Berardini on Jennifer Bolande\"|last=Berardini|first=Andrew|date=|website=Artforum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=de Brugerolle|first=Marie|date=|title=Scoping Things on the Cutting Edge: A conversation between Jennifer Bolande and Marie de Brugerolle|url=https://jbolande.files.wordpress.com/2018/12/Mousse-Magazine_MARIE-DE-BRUGEROLLE-JENNIFER-BOLANDE-D.pdf|journal=Mousse Magazine|volume=Issue 65|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nBolande earned a BFA from [[NSCAD University|Nova Scotia College of Art & Design]] in 1979. She is a Professor in [[New Genres]] in the Department of Art at [[UCLA]]<ref name=\"Jennifer Bolande\" />. She lives and works in LA and Joshua Tree, California.\n\n== Solo exhibitions ==\n\n* ''The Composition of Decomposition'', [http://magentaplains.com/exhibitions/jennifer-bolande Magenta Plains], New York (2020)\n* ''The Composition of Decomposition'', Pio Pico, Los Angeles (2018)\n* ''Measured Against What'', Green Gallery, Chicago (2014)\n* ''Landmarks, a Survey Exhibition'', Luckman Gallery, Cal State Los Angeles (2012)\n* ''Landmarks, a Survey Exhibition'', [[Institute of Contemporary Art, Philadelphia|Institute of Contemporary Art, Philadelphia, PA]]\n* ''Landmarks, a Survey Exhibition'', Institute of Visual Arts, INOVA, Wisconsin, MI (2010)\n* ''Mathematics and Myths of Yesterday and Today'', Thomas Solomon & Cottage Home, Los Angeles\n* ''Plywood Curtains'', West of Rome Public Art, citywide installation, Los Angeles\n* ''Smoke Screens'', Alexander and Bonin, New York (2008)\n* ''Earthquake'', Alexander and Bonin, New York (2004)\n*''Globe Sightings'',Fotohof, Salzburg, Austria (2003)\n* ''Globe Sightings'', Alexander and Bonin, New York (2001)\n* ''The City at Night,'' Alexander and Bonin, New York (1999)\n* [[MoMA PS1|MoMA P.S.1]], Long Island City, New York\n* ''Road Movie'', John Gibson Gallery, New York (1995)\n* Kunstraum M\u00fcnchen, Munich, Germany\n* Kunsthalle Palazzo, Liestal, Switzerland\n* Richard Telles Fine Art, Los Angeles (1994)\n* [[Metro Pictures Gallery|Metro Pictures]], New York (1992)\n* Urbi et Orbi, Paris France (1990)\n* Galleri Nordanstad-Skarstedt, Stockholm, Sweden\n* [[Margo Leavin|Margo Leavin Gallery]], Los Angeles (1989)\n* [[Metro Pictures Gallery|Metro Pictures]], New York (1988)\n* Galerie Sophia Ungers, Cologne, Germany (1987)\n* Nature Morte, New York (1986)\n* [[Artists Space|Artists Space, New York]] (1983)\n* [[The Kitchen|The Kitchen, New York]] (1982)\n\n==Group exhibitions==\n\n*''Celebration of Our Enemies'', [[Hammer Museum]], Los Angeles, CA;\n*''Readymades Are For Everyone'', [[Swiss Institute Contemporary Art New York|Swiss Institute]], New York, NY;\n*''Brand New: Art and Commodity in the 1980s'', [[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden|Hirschorn Museum]], Washington, DC;\n*''Make Believe'', [http://www.magentaplains.com/ Magenta Plains], New York, NY;\n*''Arcadias'', [http://www.magentaplains.com/ Magenta Plains], New York, NY;\n*''Skyscraper'', [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago]];\n* ''The Pathos of Things'', Carriage Trade, New York; \n*''Artists and Architecture; Variable Dimensions'', du Pavillon de l\u2019Arsenale, Paris\n* ''Private Investigations'', [[Presentation House Gallery]], Vancouver, BC; \n* ''Mixed Use Manhattan'', [[Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sofia]], Madrid; \n*This Will Have Been, Art Love and Politics in the 1980\u2019s, Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago; Walker Art Center, Minneapolis, and ICA, Boston, MA\n*Phot(o)bject, [[The Polygon Gallery|Presentation House Gallery]], Vancouver, BC\n*''Deep Storage'', [[Haus der Kunst]], Munich; Kunstmuseum, Dusseldorf; PSI, New York; Henry Art Gallery, Seattle, WA\n* ''The Readymade Boomerang'', Eighth [[Biennale of Sydney]], Australia; \n* ''Status of Sculpture'', [[Institute of Contemporary Arts]], London.<ref name=\"Jennifer Bolande\">{{cite web|title=Jennifer Bolande - Professor, New Genres|url=http://www.art.ucla.edu/faculty/bolande.html|publisher=UCLA|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Fellowships==\nBolande is the recipient of fellowships from the [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation]], the [[New York Foundation for the Arts]], the Lower Manhattan Cultural Council, the Tesuque Foundation, the Canadian Council on the Arts, the Elizabeth Firestone Graham Foundation, and the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts.<ref name=\"Jennifer Bolande\"/>\n\n== Artist Books ==\nBolande has published several artist books including ''The Times'', 2016, ''Excavation Volumes 1-35'', 2016, ''Short Story'', 2015, and ''Space Photography'', 2010, published by [https://www.zgpress.com/ ZG Press].\n\n== Selected Public Collections ==\nBolande has work in several collections of public museums and institutions including\n\n* [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles|MOCA, Los Angeles]]\n*[[MAMCO]], Geneva\n* [[Centre Pompidou|Centre Pompidou, Paris]]\n* [[Moderna Museet|Moderna Museet, Stockholm]]\n* [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]]\n*[[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]]\n* [[Hammer Museum|Hammer Museum, Los Angeles]]\n*[[P\u00e9rez Art Museum Miami|Miami Art Museum]]\n* [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art|LACMA]], Los Angeles\n*[[Israel Museum|The Israel Museum]], Jerusalem\n* [[Palm Springs Art Museum]], Palm Springs\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://jbolande.com/ Jennifer Bolande website]\n*[https://vimeo.com/bolande Jennifer Bolande Vimeo]\n*[https://jbolande.files.wordpress.com/2018/12/Mousse-Magazine_MARIE-DE-BRUGEROLLE-JENNIFER-BOLANDE-D.pdf Scoping Things on the Cutting Edge: A conversation between Jennifer Bolande and Marie de Brugerolle, '''Mousse Magazine''']\n*[https://wepresent.wetransfer.com/story/jennifer-bolande-visible-distancesecond-sight-desert-x/ Jennifer Bolande \u201cIt draws attention to the transition between here and there\u201d Interview with Rob Anderson, WePresent, 2017]\n* [http://www.eastofborneo.org/articles/remembering-jack-goldstein Jennifer Bolande, \"Remembering Jack Goldstein,\" ''Afterall'' 7 (Spring/Summer 2003).]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bolande, Jennifer}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Artists from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles faculty]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:NSCAD University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American artist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Jennifer Bolande\n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1957<!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place = [[Cleveland, Ohio]]\n| death_date = <!-- {{De